Both `SO_RCVTIMEO` and `SO_SNDTIMEO` socket options are standardized across various Unix-like operating systems and are available in BSD family operating systems such as FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and DragonFly BSD. These options set the receive and send timeouts, respectively, for socket operations.

- `SO_RCVTIMEO`: This option sets a timeout for receiving operations. If data is not received within the specified time period, the `recv` call (or equivalent) will return with a timeout error.

- `SO_SNDTIMEO`: This option sets a timeout for sending operations. If the data is not successfully sent within the specified time period, the `send` call (or equivalent) will return with a timeout error.

These socket options take a `struct timeval` as the parameter in their `setsockopt` calls, where you specify the timeout value in seconds and microseconds. The options are particularly useful for ensuring an application does not block indefinitely on I/O operations on a socket.

Here is an example in C of how to set these timeouts on a socket in a BSD-derived operating system:

```c
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/socket.h>
#include <netinet/in.h>
#include <netinet/tcp.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int sockfd; // Socket file descriptor

// Set receive timeout
struct timeval recv_timeout;
recv_timeout.tv_sec = 10; // 10 seconds
recv_timeout.tv_usec = 0; // 0 microseconds
if (setsockopt(sockfd, SOL_SOCKET, SO_RCVTIMEO, &recv_timeout, sizeof(recv_timeout)) < 0) {
    perror("Error setting receive timeout");
}

// Set send timeout
struct timeval send_timeout;
send_timeout.tv_sec = 10; // 10 seconds
send_timeout.tv_usec = 0; // 0 microseconds
if (setsockopt(sockfd, SOL_SOCKET, SO_SNDTIMEO, &send_timeout, sizeof(send_timeout)) < 0) {
    perror("Error setting send timeout");
}
```

These options are widely supported and should work on most BSD systems as well as other Unix-like systems including Linux. However, it is always a good idea to check the current system documentation for any specific behaviors or limitations related to these options.

`net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` is a sysctl setting in Linux that controls the TCP receive buffer size. It specifically tunes the minimum, default, and maximum buffer sizes that the kernel will use for TCP socket receive buffers. The `tcp_rmem` setting is a vector of three integers:

- The first value is the minimum receive buffer for each TCP connection.
- The second value is the default receive buffer assigned to each TCP connection.
- The third value is the maximum receive buffer that can be allocated for a TCP connection.

For example, you might see values like `4096  87380  6291456`, which would imply:

- Min: 4096 bytes (4 KB)
- Default: 87380 bytes (~85 KB)
- Max: 6291456 bytes (~6 MB)

To check the current `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` setting on your system, you can use the `sysctl` command:

```sh
sysctl net.ipv4.tcp_rmem
```

As for retrieving these values with `getsockopt`, you cannot get the sysctl settings directly; instead, `getsockopt` with the `SO_RCVBUF` option will give you the current receive buffer size of a specific socket. Note that the value returned may be doubled from what you set due to kernel internals that account for bookkeeping overhead.

Here's how you can use `getsockopt` to get the receive buffer size for a TCP socket in C:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/socket.h>

int sockfd; // Assume this is an open socket file descriptor for a TCP connection
int receive_buffer_size;
socklen_t optlen;

optlen = sizeof(receive_buffer_size);
if (getsockopt(sockfd, SOL_SOCKET, SO_RCVBUF, &receive_buffer_size, &optlen) < 0) {
    perror("getsockopt");
    // Handle error
} else {
    printf("Receive buffer size = %d\n", receive_buffer_size);
}
```

This code will print the size of the receive buffer for `sockfd`. It will not directly reflect the third parameter of the `tcp_rmem` setting because that is a system-wide limit and not a property of an individual socket. Remember that the actual amount of buffer memory reserved for a socket may be twice the size that was set using `SO_RCVBUF` due to overhead. The overhead is there so data that is en-route (packets that have been received by the kernel but not yet read by the application) can also be accommodated.
